title: Brooklyn: Kings Highway - 40th Street (East)

text:
Kings Highway, north from East 40th Street, showing Capt. Albert Emmonhs' House at the extreme right, built by him in 1856. This house later became the Joseph Fleming House. The entire row of houses were demolished in
May 1925.
March 1925.
Eugene L, Armbruster Collection.
title: Brooklyn: Kings Highway - 40th Street (East)

text:
4005 Kings Highway, at the N.E. corner of East 40th Street, showing the J. B. Hendrickson house, known once as No. 60 Kouwenhoven Lane. It was occupied by the Hendrickson family until 1873 and later by John Hegeman,
whose family still occupy it.
March 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

text:
(1)
East 40th Street, west side, north from King's Highway. A view of the Flatlands Dutch Reform Church, and its Cemetery, dating from the 17th century.
April 27, 1931.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, showing headstones of several members of the Schenck family interred in the cemetery partially seen in view one. Note headstones
spelled with the name Schenky.
About 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

text:
Kings Highway, at the N.. corner of East 40th Street. A view of the
Platlands Dutch Reformed Church and Sunday School.
April 27, 1931.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
Two Norway maple trees dedicated to the ancestors of the Van Voorhees and Wyckoff families, who as colonists worshiped in this church, were planted yesterday in the graveyard adjoining the church, according to the
New York Times of May 23, 1938.
